al fact. Thus, satirical banknotes were objects that broke down the distinction between paper money and graphic satire ​altogether.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBank notes in art. 0aEnglish wit and humor, Pictorial. 0aPaper money designzGreat BritainxHistory.  aBritain, UK, United Kingdom, England, comedy, comics, satire, satirical comedy, art, money, materialism, London, inflation, moral, morals, graphic satire, prints, 18th century, eighteenth century, 1700s, media, satirical banknotes, history, policy, politics, economics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781644532713?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644532713423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644532713/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA5EBK